{"id":854,"date":"2009-06-16T07:02:51","date_gmt":"2009-06-16T12:02:51","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/in_brief_jello-o_what_if.php"},"modified":"2009-06-16T07:02:51","modified_gmt":"2009-06-16T12:02:51","slug":"in_brief_jello_o_what_if","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/in_brief_jello_o_what_if.php","title":{"rendered":"In Brief: Jello-O, What If&hellip;?"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><img src=\"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/inbrief_fake_jello.jpg\" alt=\"Jell-O Student Project\" \/><\/p>\n<div class=\"in_brief\">It&#8217;s not common that I&#8217;ll bring up student work in Brand New, but this effort by semi-recent graduate of Academy of Art University, Richard Perez is worth celebrating. While at SVA, Bryony and I used to have our students redesign the packaging for Sherwin-Williams paints, something mundane and ordinary that you don&#8217;t think much about, but when people are reviewing your portfolio it&#8217;s a brand they know, can connect with and are able to see the improvements the design makes. This redesign of the Jell-O packaging achieves exactly that: It takes the mundane and ordinary conventions of the Jell-O boxes and presents a vivid interpretation of what it could be. <a href=\"http:\/\/skinnyships.com\/index.php?\/design\/jello\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Many more images at Richard&#8217;s site<\/a>.<\/div>\n<p><span class=\"small\"><strong>Thanks to Dawn H. Buscher for the tip.<\/strong><\/span><\/p>","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<img src=\"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/images\/excerpt_empty.gif\" alt=\"Excerpt Empty\" \/>","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"episode_type":"","audio_file":"","duration":"","filesize":"","date_recorded":"","ex